Global Early Childhood Education Initiatives: A Data-Driven Exploration

Author

Caitlin McGonagle

🌍Global Early Childhood Education Initiatives: A Data-Driven Exploration🌍

Education can be regarded as a catalyst for children and their future, yet access remains deeply unequal worldwide. As will be evidenced, economic conditions, geographical location, societal norms and gender biases shape the extent to which children receive an educational foundation.

A variety of factors can influence early education programme participation (among children aged 36-59 months). By exploring the data, we can understand how investing early can yield greater benefits for both the child and their environment.

Code 
from plotnine import *
import pandas as pd

df = full_data.to_pandas()
df_clean = df.dropna(subset=["continent", "obs_value"])

bar_data = df_clean.groupby("continent", as_index=False)["obs_value"].mean()

(
     ggplot(bar_data, aes(x="continent", y="obs_value", fill="obs_value"))
    +geom_col()
    + geom_text(aes(label=round(bar_data["obs_value"], 1)), va="bottom", nudge_y=2)
+ scale_fill_gradient(low="#cce5ff", high="#004080")


     + labs(
        title="A Regional Breakdown:\n Where Do More Children Attend Early Childhood Programmes?",
         x="Continent",
          y="Participation (%)",
         fill="Avg %"
    )
    +  theme_minimal()
   +  theme(plot_title=element_text(ha='center', va='top'))


)

🧠 This graphic demonstrates the disparate access across world regions to early education initiatives.

📈 As illustrated, Europe and South America lead the landscape with the highest average enrolment rates, suggesting greater investment in or accessibility for the populations of these regions.

⚠️ However, it should be caveated that a number of Western countries are omitted from the dataset for Europe, meaning the continent’s average may not fully reflect the region’s actual performance.

📉 On the opposite end of the spectrum, Africa and Oceania (Australia and New Zealand not included) show significantly lower participation rates.

Code 
global_time_data = (

    full_data
  .filter(
      pl.col("indicator").str.contains("36") &
        (pl.col("sex") == "Total")
    )
)
Code 
global_avg = (
  global_time_data
  .group_by("time_period")
    .agg(pl.col("obs_value").mean().alias("avg_participation"))
.sort("time_period")
  .to_pandas()
)
Code 

(
    ggplot(global_avg, aes(x="time_period", y="avg_participation"))
    + geom_line(color="#2E8B57", size=1.5)
    + geom_point(color="#2E8B57", size=2)
    + labs(
       title="Global Yearly Early Childhood Education Participation Rate",
       x="Year",
    y="Average Participation (%)"
    )
    + theme_minimal()
)

🧠 The time-series graph illustrates the global average participation rate in education programmes (for children aged 36-59 months), spanning a 23 year time period from 2000 to 2023.

📈 A general upward trend can be observed from 2000 to 2010, followed by a notable increase in participation for several years following 2010. This trend could reflect greater access or also be representative of better data reporting.

📉 The other sharp drop in average participation recorded in 2023 is a likely reflection of a lack data available rather than an actual decline in programme participation.

📊 Overall, the visual indicates steady progress in early childhood programme participation on a global scale over time, although gaps in data reporting and year-to-year inconsistencies should be taken into consideration when interpreting the trend.

Code 
indicator1 = pl.read_csv("unicef_indicator_1.csv")
metadata = pl.read_csv(

    "unicef_metadata.csv",
    schema_overrides={"Population, total": pl.Float64}
)
Code 
metadata = metadata.rename({"year": "time_period"})
full_data = indicator1.join(metadata, on=["country", "time_period"], how="left")
Code 
scatter_data = (
    full_data

    .filter(
        (pl.col("indicator").str.contains("36")) &
        (pl.col("sex") == "Total") &
        pl.col("GDP per capita (constant 2015 US$)").is_not_null() &
        pl.col("obs_value").is_not_null()
    )
  .select(["obs_value", "GDP per capita (constant 2015 US$)", "Population, total", "country"])
   .drop_nulls()
    .to_pandas()
)
Code 
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
Code 
X = scatter_data[["GDP per capita (constant 2015 US$)"]].values

y = scatter_data["obs_value"].values



regressor = LinearRegression()
regressor.fit(X, y)

y_pred = regressor.predict(X)

plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
plt.scatter(scatter_data["GDP per capita (constant 2015 US$)"], scatter_data["obs_value"], color='blue', label='Data points', alpha=0.5)
plt.plot(scatter_data["GDP per capita (constant 2015 US$)"], y_pred, color='green', label='Linear Regression Line', linewidth=2)
plt.title('GDP vs Early Education: The Economic Impact on Early Education', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('GDP per Capita (US$)', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Early Childhood Education Participation (%)', fontsize=12)
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.5)
plt.show()

💡 HIGHER INVESTMENT = HIGHER RETURNS 💡

The scatterplot reveals a positive correlation between early childhood education participation and GDP per capita of a country.

Countries with higher rates of participation tend to experience stronger economic performance (in terms of the measure GDP), suggesting that laying the foundation of an educated population can promote economic growth.

However, it should be noted, as demonstrated, some outliers indicate that economic wealth alone doesn’t guarantee early education access, while the relationship is evident, correlation does not imply direct causality

import geopandas as gp
import polars as pl
Code 
world_map = gp.read_file("https://public.opendatasoft.com/api/explore/v2.1/catalog/datasets/world-administrative-boundaries/exports/shp")
Code 
indicator1 = pl.read_csv("unicef_indicator_1.csv")

metadata = pl.read_csv(
     "unicef_metadata.csv",

        schema_overrides={"Population, total": pl.Float64}
)
Code 
metadata = metadata.rename({"year": "time_period"})
full_data = indicator1.join(metadata, on=["country", "time_period"], how="left")
Code 
world_map_data = full_data.select(["country", "obs_value"]).drop_nulls()
Code 
merged_data = world_map.merge(world_map_data.to_pandas(), left_on="name", right_on="country", how="outer")
Code 
ax = merged_data.plot(
     column="obs_value",
     cmap="seismic",

      legend=True,
      legend_kwds={'label': "Participation Rate (%)"},

     figsize=(15, 6)
)

ax.set_title("Mapping Early Childhood Education Participation Across the Globe", fontsize=16)
ax.set_xlabel("Longitude")
ax.set_ylabel("Latitude")

Text(142.97222222222223, 0.5, 'Latitude')

Global education participation varies hugely with trends in participation seen within regions of geographical proximity.

  • Higher enrolment (red) is experienced in parts of Central Asia, Eastern Europe and South America
  • Lower rates of participation (blue) can be seen throughout Africa, the Middle East & South Asia.

Early education is not just a stepping stone- it’s a global equaliser.

Across the globe, countries with greater participation rates in early education initiatives noticeably enjoy stronger economic activity and longer life expectancies.

While any one initiative can not be perfect due to gender, income or geography disparities, the data reinforces a clear message:

🗣Early Investment in the Youth Yields Long-Term Gains for Society 🗣
